@section Continuation objects


Continuation objects are memory blocks referenced by machine words
tagged as vectors, whose first word is tagged as continuation:

@example
|----------------|----------| reference to continuation
  heap pointer    vector tag

|----------------|----------| first word of continuation
 all set to zero  vector tag
@end example

@noindent
the layout of a continuation memory block is:

@example
|-----|-----|-----|-----|
  tag   top  size  next
@end example

To understand the contents of a continuation object, we have to recall
how the Scheme stack is used:

@example
 high memory
|            |
|------------|
|            | <-- pcb->frame_base
|------------|
| used word  | <-- pcb->frame_base - wordsize
|------------|
|     .      |
|     .      |
|     .      |
|------------|
| free word  | <-- pcb->frame_pointer
|------------|
|     .      |
|     .      |
|     .      |
|------------|
| free word  | <-- pcb->stack_base
|------------|
|            |
  low memory
@end example

@noindent
and remember that @code{pcb->frame_base} references a word that is
one--off the end of the stack segment; so the first word in the stack
is:

@example
pcb->frame_base - wordsize
@end example

@noindent
A continuation references the portion of the Scheme stack memory segment
between @code{frame_base} and @code{frame_pointer}.

There are two kinds of continuation objects:

@table @dfn
@item Scheme continuations
Represent a Scheme continuation.  They are expliticly created by
@func{call/cc}, but also used to represent a previous Scheme code
execution when the allocated Scheme stack runs out of space.

@item system continuations
Represent a C continuation.  They are used by the @ffi{} to save the C
execution context just before calling back to Scheme from C code.
@end table

The fields of a Scheme continuation are:

@table @code
@item top
Untagged pointer referencing the first free word on the Scheme stack.

@item size
Number of bytes used on the Scheme stack, @strong{not} counting the free
word referenced by the frame pointer.

@item next
Tagged pointer referencing a continuation object; it represents the
continuation to go back to after the execution of tthis continuation is
finished.  This ``going back'' is performed by the C function
@cfunc{ik_exec_code}.
@end table

The fields of a Scheme continuation are:

@table @code
@item top
Untagged memory pointer referencing the C language stack last saved by
Scheme code; it is the content of the field @code{pcb->system_stack} at
the time this system continuation object was created.

@item size
Unused.

@item next
Tagged memory pointer referencing the next continuation; it is the
content of the field @code{pcb->next_k} at the time this system
continuation object was created.
@end table

Whatever the kind, usually a continuation is created and then saved in
the field @code{pcb->next_k} in such a way that continuation objects
create a linked list:

@example
        next_k
|------|------|-----| PCB
          |
          v     next
       |-------|----| continuation
                  |
                  v     next
               |-------|----| continuation
                          |
                           --> NULL
@end example

